Mick Moloney Irish-American Music and Popular Culture Papers

Contents

Series I: General, 1806-2011

langmaterial

English

Extent

14 boxes

Scope and Content Note

Series I: General, 1806-2011 consists of subject files concerning to Dr. Moloney's professional life as a performer, promoter, producer, and fieldworker. Materials include newsletters produced by various Irish-American "Celtic" Societies; scholarly journals on music and ethnicity; photocopies of early 20th century Irish-American newspapers; business and personal correspondence; an extensive collection (referred to as "Bookings") of contracts and correspondence detailing Dr. Moloney's performance engagements; files documenting behind-the-scenes studio work ("Recording Projects"); financial records and ephemera pertaining to major and independent labels, such as Green Linnet, Shanachie, Topic, and Transatlantic, with emphasis on marketing and the business models applied to Irish music starting in the 1970s. Of particular note is a complete run of the Shanachie label's newsletter and a collection of record catalogs dating back to the 1920s.

The series also contains materials concerning Dr. Moloney's involvement in numerous federally funded projects, including the Smithsonian Institution Festival of American Folklife (1976), the Chicago Ethnic Arts Project (1977), the Green Fields of America ensemble, the 1982 Knoxville's World's Fair, the International Village Fair in Philadelphia (1987), the Philadelphia Ceili Group Festival, and the Irish Week at the Augusta Heritage Center in Elkins, West Virginia. Other projects are also documented, such as the development for the proposed multi-part series for Radio Telefis Eireann called The Green Fields of America and Emigrants and Exiles.

Series II: Individuals, 1879-2010

Extent

5 boxes

Scope and Content Note

Series II: Individuals, 1879-2010 consists of materials collected by Dr. Moloney throughout the course of his academic and professional activities concerning specific individuals and groups. The majority of these individuals and groups are Irish or Irish-American, are closely associated with Irish traditional music, and often performers. Others are Irish or Irish-American academics, poets, and writers, including the Philadelphia-based historian Dennis Clark. Of particular note are materials related to Dr. Moloney himself that provide an insight into his private and public lives. Included in this series is a small set of materials given to Dr. Moloney by fiddler and radio host Tommy Caulfield, including ledger books, correspondence, radio receipts, advertisements, and concert programs which provide documentation on the Irish Musicians' Association and the Irish Musicians' Union in Philadelphia beginning in the 1940s.

Series III: Academic, 1889-2011

Extent

3 boxes

Scope and Content Note

Series III: Academic, 1889-2011 consists of research and teaching materials accrued by Dr. Moloney while acquiring his PhD from the University of Pennsylvania and during his teaching assignments at Villanova University, New York University, Georgetown University, Boston College. Materials include syllabi, lectures notes, reading lists, correspondence, and handwritten research notes. Also included are photocopied scholarly journal articles and student papers of various folklore and ethnicity topics.

Series IV: Song and Music Collecting, 1867-2000

Extent

2 boxes

Scope and Content Note

Series IV: Song and Music Collecting, 1867-2000 contains lyrics, tunes, and songs in published and manuscript form collected by Dr. Moloney for research, personal, and performance use. Of particular note are John Ward's Private Collection of Irish Comic Songs, twenty photocopied songsters, and manuscripts of dance tunes, some of which are Moloney's compositions.

Series V: Concert Memorabilia, 1971-2011

Extent

2 boxes

Scope and Content Note

Series V: Concert Memorabilia, 1971-2011 consists of programs, flyers, brochures, and ephemera accumulated during Dr. Moloney's performance career. Of particular note are many oversized items, including early Johnstons posters and a Spanish-language poster promoting the 1985 Festival of Mountain Music and Dance Central American tour.

Series VI: Photographs, circa 1930-2002

Extent

8 boxes

Scope and Content Note

Series VI: Photographs, circa 1930-2002 consists of slides, prints, and negatives of performers, events, and venues that appear in both the Papers and Field Recordings subcollections. Subjects with extensive coverage include Dr. Moloney's performing partnerships with Eugene O'Donnell, Robbie O'Connell, and Jimmy Keane; Moloney's package tours of Ireland and Scotland; the 1987 International Village Fair hosted by Philadelphia's International House; step dancing classes and competitions (some featuring Jean and Cara Butler); and slides prepared for Dr. Moloney's lectures. Of particular note are contact sheets documenting informal gathering of musicians and a 35 mm print of Did Your Mother Come From Ireland?, Dr. Moloney's 1981film on the Mulvihill School of Irish Music in the Bronx.

Series VII: Archived Websites, April 2014-ongoing

Extent

2 websites in two archived websites.

Scope and Content Note

The website includes Mick Moloney's event and concert listings, yearly cultural tours in Ireland, his discography, reviews, and his writings.

Accruals

New site crawls are accrued semiannually.

Appraisal

Crawl was limited to domains and subdomains of mickmoloney.com in order to remain within the collection scope and data constraints.

Physical Characteristics and Technical Requirements

Due to technical or privacy issues, archived websites may not be exact copies of the original website at the time of the web crawl. Certain file types will not be captured dependent on how they are embedded in the site. Other parts of websites that the crawler has difficulty capturing includes Javascript, streaming content, database-driven content, and highly interactive content. Full-Text searches of archived websites are available at https://archive-it.org/organizations/567.
